			<h1>1. Deduction for Interest Paid on Housing Loan</h1>

			<p><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;A home loan must be taken for the purchase/construction of a house and the construction of the<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;house must be completed within 5 years from the end of financial year in which loan was taken.</p>

			<p class="p1"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;If you are paying EMI for the housing loan, it has two components – interest payment<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;and principal repayment.</p>

			<p class="p2"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;The interest portion of the EMI paid for the year can be claimed as a deduction from your<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;total income up to a maximum of Rs 2 lakh under Section 24.</p>

			<p class="p3"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;From Assessment Year 2018-19 onwards, the maximum deduction for interest paid<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;on Self Occupied house property is Rs 2 Lakh.</p>

			<p class="p4"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;For let out property, there is no upper limit for claiming interest.However, the overall<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;loss one can claim under the head of House Property is restricted to Rs 2 lakh only.</p>

			<p class="p5"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;This Deduction can be claimed from the year in which construction of the house is<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;completed.</p>

		</div>

		<div class="sec-3">
				
			<img class="main-img" src="Tax_Benefit3.jpg">
			<img class="icon" src="icon.png"/>

			<h1>2. Deduction in respect of interest paid towards<br>&ensp;&ensp;home loan during pre-construction period</h1>
 
			<p><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;Say, you bought an under-construction property and have not moved in yet. But you are paying<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;the EMIs.</p>

			<p class="p1"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;In this case, your eligibility to claim interest on the home loan as a deduction begins<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;only upon completion of construction or immediately if you buy a fully constructed property.</p>

			<p class="p2"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;So does this mean you would not enjoy any tax benefits on the interest paid during the period<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;falling between the borrowing of loan and completion of construction? No. Let’s understand why.</p>

			<p class="p3"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;The income tax law provides for the claim of such interest also, called the pre-construction<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;interest, as a deduction in <b>five equal instalments</b> starting from the year in which the property is<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;acquired or construction is completed, over and above the deduction you are otherwise eligible<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;to claim from your house property income. However, the maximum eligibility remains capped<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;at Rs 2 lakh.</p>

		</div>

		<div class="sec-4">
				
			<img class="main-img" src="Tax_Benefit4.jpg">
			<img class="icon" src="icon.png"/>
			<h1>3. Deduction on Principal repayment</h1>
			
			<p><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;The Principal portion of the EMI paid for the year is allowed as deduction under Section 80C.</p>
			
			<p class="p1"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;The maximum amount that can be claimed is up to <b>Rs 1.5 lakh.</b></p>
			
			<p class="p2"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;But to claim this deduction, the house property should not be sold<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;within 5 years of possession.</p>

			<p class="p3"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp; Otherwise, the deduction claimed earlier will be added back to your income<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;in the year of sale.</p>
				
		</div>

		<div class="sec-5">
			
			<img class="main-img" src="Tax_Benefit5.jpg">
			<img class="icon" src="icon.png"/>
			<h1>4.Deduction For Stamp Duty and Registration Charges</h1>

			<p><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;Besides claiming the deduction for principal repayment, a deduction for stamp duty and<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;registration charges can also be claimed u/s 80C but within the overall limit of Rs  1.5 lakhs.</p> 

			<p class="p1"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;However, it can be claimed only in the year in which these expenses are incurred.</p>

		</div>

		<div class="sec-6">
				
			<img class="main-img" src="Tax_Benefit6.png">
			<img class="icon" src="icon.png"/>
			<h1>5.Additional deduction under section 80EE</h1>
			
			<p><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;Additional deduction under Section 80EE is allowed to the home buyers for maximum<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;to Rs 50,000.</p>
			
			<p class="p1"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;To claim this deduction, the amount of loan taken should be Rs 35 lakhs<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;or less and the value of the property does not exceed Rs 50 lakhs.</p>
			
			<p class="p2"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;The loan must have been sanctioned between 1st April 2016 to 31st March 2017.<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;And on the date of sanction of loan, individual does not own any other house.</p>

 			<p class="p3"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp; Section 80EE has been reintroduced effective from FY 2016-17.</p>

 			<p class="p4"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp; Earlier the deduction allowed under Sec 80EE was available for 2 years<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;FY 2013-14 and FY 2014-15 only.</p>
				
		</div>

		<div class="sec-7">
			
			<img class="main-img" src="Tax_Benefit7.png">
			<img class="icon" src="icon.png"/>
			<h1>6.Additional deduction under section 80EEA</h1>

			<p><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;The budget 2019 has introduced additional deduction under Section 80EEA for home buyers<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;for maximum up to Rs 1,50,000. </p> 

			<p class="p1"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;To claim this deduction, the stamp value of the property does not exceed Rs 45 lakhs.</p>

			<p class="p2"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;The loan must have been sanctioned between 1 April 2019 to 31 March 2020.</p> 

			<p class="p3"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;And on the date of sanction of loan, individual does not own any other house.</p>

			<p class="p4"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;The individual should not also be eligible to claim deduction under section 80EE.</p>

		</div>

		<div class="sec-8">
				
			<img class="main-img" src="Tax_Benefit8.png">
			<img class="icon" src="icon.png"/>
			<h1>7.Deduction for Joint Home Loan</h1>
			
			<p><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;If the loan is taken jointly, then each of the loan holders can claim a deduction for home loan<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;interest up to Rs 2 lakh each and principal repayment u/s 80C up to Rs 1.5 lakh<br>&ensp;&ensp;&ensp;each in their individual tax returns.</p>
			
			<p class="p1"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;To claim this deduction, they should also be co-owners of the property taken on loan.</p>
			
			<p class="p2"><i class="fa fa-long-arrow-right" aria-hidden="true"></i>&ensp;So, loan taken jointly with your family can help you claim a larger tax benefit.</p>
				
		</div>

